Attributes.Value: The root content type defines attributes that will be shared by all content types. Every content type descriptor will derive from the root content type, either directly or indirectly.
The friendly name of the topic. If omitted, the key ("Folder Name") will be used instead. This is useful since the key cannot contain spaces or special symbols, since it is part of the topic's URL.
The name of the folder.  Should not contain spaces or special reserved characters such as '/', ':' or '&'.  Will be concatenated with parent Folder Names to generate the URL.
Allows for the topic to inherit its Attributes (e.g., Key, Title, etc.) from the selected topic, thus centralizing content.
Determines whether or not to display the topic in the navigation. Hidden pages can still be seen by customers and crawled by search engines.

Prevents access to the page via the website. Useful for drafting pages that aren't ready to go live, or for temporarily deleting a page that you may want to republish later, without losing its content or history.

Provides the last modified date and time for the Topic. This is automatically generated by the server based on Coordinated Universal Time (i.e., Greenwich Mean Time). It can be displayed on a web page using the customer's local time, if known.

Provides user information (e.g., account name) for the current editing user. If access to the OnTopic Editor requires authentication, then this will automatically be populated with the user name supplied by the authentication provider.

Containers provide a basic structure for organizing topics. Containers are not rendered as public facing webpages. Optionally, a container may be limited to a set of content types to help enforce a data model.
By default, child pages will display menu items from their root container. If the navigation root is set, however, then this will be used as the menu for all child pages.

Containers are not intended to be rendered as web pages and are automatically excluded from indexes. This optional additionally excludes all child topics from the sitemap. This is useful for areas of the topic tree which are not public. This does not prevent pages from being indexed; if pages are publicly available, they will not be displayed in the sitemap, but can still be crawled by search engines.

Provides a list of content types that can be created under this container. By default, all implicitly permitted content types (e.g., page, video, slideshow) can be created. This allows those to be overwritten, thus offering tighter control over the data model.
Primary HTML content for the page body.

The title that will be used in the HTML header.  This will be displayed in the title bar of the web browser, and also used as the default page title by search engines.  For this reason, the meta title is useful for search engine optimization (SEO). It may be useful to include additional context in the meta title than the main page title.

The description that will be used in the HTML header.  This is not generally displayed to the user, but some search engines will honor it for the default description of a page. For this reason, it may be useful for search engine optimization (SEO).

The keywords that will be used in the HTML header.  Keywords should be delimited using commas. These are not displayed to the user, although search engines use them to help match user search terms to appropriate pages. For this reason, it may be useful for search engine optimization (SEO)—and especially for specific terms that are relevant to customers, but don't appear in the page body.

The URL that the navigation item should redirect to.  If left blank, the page is rendered using the appropriate template.  This field is useful for pages that need to be included in the navigation, but live outside the navigation root. It is also useful for pages that have been moved, as it allows the original location to be redirected to a new location.
Provides a title that is specifically used for the navigation; this should be shorter than either the Page Title or Subtitle.
(Optional) text to be displayed as a highlighted subheader at the top of the main content area.

By default, all pages will be available for indexing from search engines—even if they're hidden. By enabling this, we allow pages to be optionally hidden from search engines. This excludes the current topic from the sitemap, and also introduces the noindex HTML metatag.
Provides a list of content items which can optionally be grouped by categories. Items can be added, removed, edited, or reordered under the Items tab.
Each content item will be displayed on the web page. Content items can be drag-and-dropped in order to change their order. Click on an existing item to modify, rename, or delete it.

Optionally establishes a set of categories that the content items can be associated with. If more than one category is created, then a dropdown list will be displayed with each content item allowing it to be associated with a category. Templates may then use this to group content items by category.

If enabled, instructs the template to provide a list of topics at the top of the page, with each one linking to the content items within the page. This is useful for lengthy lists that require scrolling to view, as it offers customers a quick overview.
Optionally overrides the default label for the index. Defaults to "Contents".
Provides a list of content which are displayed on the site as a slideshow. Individual content slides can be added, removed, edited, and reordered under the Slides tab.
The type of transition to use when presenting a new slide.
Provides a collection of slides, which will be displayed as part of a carousel in the page template.

Provides a simple page with a single video. The video URL should be loaded via HTTPS to ensure it loads correctly. Ideally, a Poster URL should also be provided, which provides an image in place of the video while the actual content loads.
A brief description of the video contents.
The URL to the video file. The file is expected to be in an MP4 format.
Provides the URL to an image to display while the video is loading.
Provides a list of search results in response to a user’s search criteria.
Provides a basic, reusable template for emails generated from the application.
The URL to an image to use for the background of the the header area. The section title will be placed on top of the background image.

A page collection allows a series of pages to be grouped together. The page collection defines the information for the header—such as a title and a background image—which will be shared by all pages. Pages directly under the page collection will be displayed in the navigation. The first of those pages will be selected and displayed by default.
Represents an individual piece of content in a content list.
An optional URL that will be exposed as a link for access to additional information about the content.
An optional URL to an image to display next to the content item. This is useful for e.g. a logo when listing multiple products or companies.
Allows the content item to be associated with a category. The page template can optionally use this information to group content items by category.
Represents an individual slide within a slideshow. Each slide acts like a stand-alone page, but is displayed within a carousel.
Primary HTML content for the page body.
The target URL that the Carousel Item should link to.  If specified, the entirety of the carousel item will be treated as a hyperlink.
Represents an individual item in a lookup list. Lookup items typically just have a Folder Name (under Navigation) and, optionally, a Title for providing a user friendly name.
Container for system content types used by the OnTopic infrastructure, but not (directly) used by editors.

Each topic is associated with a content type. A content type descriptor defines what attributes will be available for each topic of that content type. Content types can be nested; attributes will be inherited from parent content types.

Provides a description of the content type which will be displayed on any pages that implement that content type. This helps editors better understand the context and purpose of the topic they are editing.

Content types are composed of multiple attributes (e.g., 'Title', 'Body').  You may add as many attributes to a content type as you need.  Attributes will automatically be inherited from parent content types.  Attributes may be created specifically for this content type, or referenced from the central repository of attributes (under Configuration: Attributes) by using the "Inherits values from…" feature under Navigation.

By default, only (explicitly) permitted content types can be created underneath a topic. If no permitted content types are selected, however, then any implicitly permitted content types will be available. This should for content types that generally make sense most places in the topic tree. (E.g., this isn't appropriate for item content types.)

Provides a list of Content Types that an editor can create under Topics of this Content Type.  If none are selected, then the editor will fall back to listing implicitly permitted content types, such as Page or Slideshow.

By default, new Topics can be created under a Topic, thus allowing a deep hierarchy.  It doesn't make sense for some Topics to have child Topics, however.  For instance, in Configuration, there is no logical benefit to having another Topic under an Attribute.  Checking this prevents users from creating child Topics using the editor (i.e., it removes the "Add Child Topic..." option from the lower-left corner).

Disable the ability for topics using this content type to be deleted via the interface. Note that these topics can still be deleted by code. This is intended to avoid inadvertent—and potentially catastrophic—deletion of key infrastructure topics, such as Configuration.

Content Types are hidden from the navigation by default, and explicitly added either by setting the Permitted Content Types, or marking them as Implicitly Permitted (both under Settings). As such, there's no need to allow Content Types to be hidden.

Represents the core attributes expected on all attribute descriptors. Attribute type descriptors (such as the NumberAttributeDescriptor) can optionally extend this list for attributes that are specific to a particular attribute type.

The display name defines how the attribute is labeled on the page.  This is usually a user-friendly version of the key attribute.  E.g., this attributes Key attribute value is 'Title' but it's Display Name attribute value is 'Display Name'.
Display groups are rendered as tabs in the editor.  They allow different attributes to be grouped together.  Be aware that display groups are case sensitive. Display groups are listed alphabetically.

Provides a friendly description for the attribute to help the editor understand the nature of the data.  This is displayed as a tooltip in the editor next to the attribute. The copy you are reading is the description for the 'Description' attribute on the AttributeDescriptor content type.

Determines where within a given tab ('Display Group') the attribute is listed when viewed in the editor.  Attributes are automatically sorted based on the Sort Order.  For instance, this attributes Sort Order is 6, putting it after the Description attribute (which has a Sort Order of 5).

Determines whether or not an attribute is visible in the Editor.  This is useful, for instance, if an attribute that was previously used is no longer needed, but you want to keep the attribute type around just in case it may be needed again in the future.
Provides a list of any attributes derived from the current attribute.

If an attribute is marked as required, then the editor will ensure that a value is provided. Note that this does not guarantee that the value exists, as the attribute may have been added to a Content Type after instances of that Content Type had already been created.

Attributes which are less than 250 characters can be stored as indexed attributes, which are easier to work with. Attributes with potentially longer values, such as HTML fields, must be stored as extended attributes, which may be stored separately (e.g., as an XML field) in the backend database.

Defines a value that the editor will automatically assign when a new topic is created—assuming the topic isn't derived from another topic, in which case it will inherit the value from that topic. This should be used with care as it potentially prevents values from being inherited by explicitly setting a local value.

Defines the value that will automatically be assigned by the application if a value isn't provided. This value will be displayed as a placeholder value, where appropriate. It is not used by the OnTopic Editor to set the value; the only purpose is to help communicate to editor's what the expected value is if the attribute is left empty.
A Boolean attribute can be set to either true or false, and will be rendered as a set of radio buttons in the editor. Boolean attribute values are stored as either “0” (false) or “1” (true).
A number attribute allows the editor to enter any numeric value, optionally within a range of values.
Determines the minimum value that the attribute can be set to. Defaults to 0.
Determines the maximum value that the attribute can be set to. Defaults to 2,147,483,647.

A date/time attribute exposes a date and/or time picker for selecting a date associated with the topic. Optionally, the date can be set to an offset from the current time; e.g., a task content type might default to setting the date one week from the current time.
Determines whether the date/time picker should include the date element.
Determines whether the date/time picker should include the time element.
Offsets the default date/time value by a specified interval. For instance, an Expiration field may have a Date/Time Offset of 1 year, setting it to expire. Defaults to zero.
Sets the units for the Date/Time Offset configuration. Defaults to "Days".

Exposes a dropdown list of files that can be found at a particular path and, optionally, within its subdirectories. In addition, the list can optionally be filtered based on a file extension and a search string, if only a subset of files are relevant.
Sets the folder location where the files that should be listed are located in.
Determines whether or not the file list should only include files from the Path, or if it should also include any files in child directories. Defaults to false.
Optionally sets the file extension of the files you wish to display. E.g., "pdf" will only display files ending in ".pdf".

Optionally sets a filter to use to limit the files returned. Can be used in conjunction with Extension. For instance, setting Filter to "Proposal" will limit the output to files that contain "Proposal" in the file name.

A file path attribute can be set to a file path or a URL. Optionally, it can be set relative to the current topic, thus allowing child topics to automatically discover URLs based on a parent topic’s configuration without needing to configure a file path for every topic. This is useful if a file tree follows the topic tree.

Determines whether or not the file path should be inherited from parent topics that have the same key set. This allows file paths to be set for a group of topics. Can be combined with RelativeToTopicPath.

Determines whether or not the calculated path should be based on the current topic hierarchy. This allows a the file server to follow the same hierarchy as the topics without having to manually set the path on every individual topic.

Assuming the file path is configured to be relative to the topic path, this sets the base path from which the path should be calculated. For example, if the topic is located at /Web/Services/Consulting/Partners/ and the base topic path is set to /Web/Services/, then the file path will look in the /Consulting/Partners/ folder.

When calculating the file path relative to the topic path, determines whether the current topic's key should be included in that path. By default, this is set to true. Developers may prefer to disable this, however, if for example, the file is named based on the current topic key, as opposed to being placed in a directory. E.g., if the current topic is at /Web/Services/Consulting/ and the file is located at /Web/Services/Consulting.pdf, it makes sense to exclude the current topic from the path.
Provides an inline instruction to users of the OnTopic Editor. No actual attribute value will be persisted to the database; its only purpose is to expose the inline instructions.
Provides instructional text associated with the attribute. This will be displayed inline on the editor.
The Last Modified Date simply stores the current date on the server, thus offering a time stamp of when the topic was last modified.
The Last Modified By attribute simply stores the currently authenticated user—or, otherwise, “System”—thus providing a record of who modified the current version of the topic.

A Nested Topic List provides a list of topics embedded that can be added, edited, deleted, or reordered within the current topic. This is useful for content with complex markup, as that markup can be centralized via the template, instead of being placed within e.g. an HTML attribute.
Explicitly sets what content types are allowed to be created as nested topics. Typically, this will only be one type, but there may be cases where multiple types are permitted.

Determines whether or not the topic list should trigger a popup window to display the nested topics. Defaults to true. Under rare circumstances, such as when a model requires multiple layers of nested topic lists (not recommended), it may make sense to disable this functionality.

A Topic List attributes provides a list of topics from a specific location—which can optionally be relative to the current topic—and saves an attribute of the selected topic as the attribute value. This is useful for constraining the value of an attribute to a list of predetermined options.
As an alternative to the Root Topic, a relative topic base can be set, which allows topics to be looked up relative to the current topic or content type descriptor.
Works in conjunction with the relative topic base, if set. The relative topic path is appended to the relative topic base to determine the source for topics.

All topic lists displaying more than one topic will include a default placeholder options with an empty value providing the user with instructions on the purpose of the selection. E.g., "Select a country…" might be used if the topic list maps to a list of countries.
By default, the topic's Key is used for the value. Optionally, this can be overwritten to use other topic attributes, such as `UniqueKey`, `TopicID`, or even `Title`.

Provides an interface for associating multiple topics with the current topic. This is similar to a relationship attribute—and, in fact, can optionally be stored as a relationship in the database. Unlike a relationship, however, the tokenized topic list is exposed as a searchable list of topics, instead of a topic tree. This can be useful when there are a large number of topics that an editor might be selecting from.
Creates an association with another topic in OnTopic. This is similar to the Tokenized Topic List, except it is limited to a single topic.
If selected, will filter by the current content type, thus ensuring the referenced topic has the same content type as the current topic.
Sets the limit for the number of topics that can be selected in the tokenized topic list. For example, setting this to 1 effectively treats the attribute as a reference to an individual topic.
Sets the limit for the number of results that can be returned from a search of the Topic Root.
If enabled, will automatically submit the form as soon as a value is selected. This is useful when the control is being used for navigation.

Determines the root topic to display for the relationship. This allows the relationship to be restricted to a particular segment of the topic graph. For example, if it's limited to "Root:Configuration:Metadata", then only topics under "Metadata" will be available for selection. Defaults to "Root".

Optionally provides an attribute key that all related topics should include, thus allowing filtering of the relationship tree. For example, it may be set to "ContentType" to filter by topics of a certain content type. Should be used in conjunction with Attribute Value Filter.

Optionally provides an attribute value that all related topics should include, thus allowing filtering of the relationship tree. For example, if Attribute Key Filter is set to "ContentType", then Attribute Value Filter may be set to "Page" to limit relationships to page topics. Must be used in conjunction with Attribute Key Filter.

Defines relationships between the current topic and multiple other topics. Optionally, that relationship can be restricted to a specific area of the topic tree, and/or of topics matching certain search criteria.
Determines whether the root topic should be displayed in the list of available relationships. Defaults to false, in which case only children of the root topic will be displayed.

When a relationship is selected, determines whether all ascendant topics should automatically be selected as well. Useful for scenarios where selecting a topic implies a relationship with all parent topics. Defaults to false.
Optionally disables the automatic expansion of the relationships tree to ensure any checked nodes are visible on load.
Displays incoming relationships originating from other topics based on a given relationship key.
Provides the name of the relationship to filter by. Defaults to the attribute key.
Provides a standard input box. Optionally, the type can be constrained based on HTML5 input types (e.g., number, URL, &c.), thus providing basic client-side validation.

Sets the HTML input type. This may impact both the presentation in the browser, as well as the client-side validation of the input. Not all browsers support each of the standard input types. Others, such as "file", aren't listed here because they aren't (yet) supported on the server.
Configures the maximum number of characters allowed in the text field. Defaults to 500.
Provides a regular expression which will be used to validate the attribute value.
Exposes a multi-line text box that can be used for longer form text entry. Note that while HTML can be entered into a text area attribute, it doesn’t provide any WYSIWYG capabilities.
Sets the number of rows—i.e., lines of normal body text—that should be displayed in the form field. Used to calculate the height of the editor. Defaults to 5.
Configures the minimum number of characters allowed in the text field. Defaults to 0.
The maximum number of characters—including any potential markup—to be permitted in the text area.
Exposes a WYSIWYG text field with a basic interface for setting formatting and styles of content.

Sets the height of the HTML window in pixels. Defaults to 20x the the number of rows, thus assuming 20px per row. For the HTML editor, Rows defaults to 20, and so the default height is effectively 400px.
Provides a test of the BooleanViewComponent.
Provides a test of the DateTimeViewComponent.
Provides a test of the FilePathViewComponent.
Provides a test of the FileListViewComponent.
Provides a test of the TokenizedTopicListViewComponent.
Provides a test of the TopicListViewComponent.
Provides a test of the TextViewComponent.
Provides a test of the TextAreaViewComponent.
Provides a test of the HtmlViewComponent.
Provides a test of the NestedTopicListViewComponent.
Provides a test of the RelationshipViewComponent.
Provides a list of metadata, typically to be associated with a dropdown list elsewhere in the editor. Lookup items can be added, removed, edited, and even reordered.

Provides a list of Lookup List Items.  These can be be bound to a TopicLookup Attribute in order to provide an enumeration of options.  This allows structured taxonomies of data to be centrally managed.
Provides a collection of Carousel Item Topics that will be displayed on the site as a slideshow of content
